{"title_page": "Gregg Gonsalves", "text_new": "'''Gregg Gonsalves''' is a global health activist, an epidemiologist, an Assistant Professor at [[Yale School of Public Health]] and an Associate Professor (adjunct) at [[Yale Law School]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://publichealth.yale.edu/people/gregg_gonsalves.profile |title=Gregg Gonsalves, PhD |publisher=[[Yale School of Public Health]] |access-date=July 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.yale.edu/gregg-gonsalves|title=Gregg Gonsalves - Yale Law School|website=law.yale.edu|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born in Mineola, New York on October 21, 1963, grew up in nearby East Meadow, NY and attended East Meadow High School.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://yalealumnimagazine.com/articles/4168-gregg-gonsalves |title=Its not just the germs |last=Shufro |first=Cathy |date=September\u2013October 2015 |work=Yale Alumni Magazine |access-date=July 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/long-island/gregg-gonsalves-macarthur-genius-1.21781209|title=Foundation honors LI native as 'genius'|website=Newsday|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> His parents were New York City school teachers, both of whom were born and grew up in Brooklyn, NY, with his father's family originally from Madeira, Portugal and his mother's family from Sicily, Italy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2018/10/04/654396763/a-global-health-evangelist-is-shocked-to-hear-hes-a-genius|title=A Global Health Evangelist Is Shocked To Hear He's A 'Genius'|last=Beaubien|first=Jason|date=October 4, 2018|website=NPR|language=en|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref> He attended [[Tufts University]] starting in 1981, but dropped out before finishing his BA degree in English and American Literature and Russian Language and Literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.tufts.edu/magazine/summer2004/features/feature4Sidebar.html|title=Tufts Magazine Archive Summer 2004|website=news.tufts.edu|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> He has two sisters, Carin Gonsalves, a physician in Philadelphia, and Dana Gonsalves, a commercial artist in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hospitals.jefferson.edu/find-a-doctor/g/gonsalves-carin-f.html|title=Carin F. Gonsalves, MD - Jefferson University Hospitals|website=hospitals.jefferson.edu|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sequelstudio.com/views/spotlight-gonsalves|title=\"How lucky am I? I get to spend my days doing what I love to do \u2014 designing with a purpose, bringing together great storytelling and design.\" {{!}} Sequel|website=sequelstudio.com|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><!--Article from 2015 gives age as 51 -->\n\n== Career ==\nHe began working with the AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power ([[ACT UP]]) in 1990, going on to co-found the [[Treatment Action Group]] (TAG) in 1992, with his colleagues from the Treatment and Data Committee of ACT UP New York, including [[Peter Staley]], [[Mark Harrington (HIV/AIDS activist)|Mark Harrington]], [[Spencer Cox (activist)|Spencer Cox]]. With TAG, he authored several reports on HIV research, including a critical review of AIDS research at the [[National Institutes of Health]], which led to a reorganization of the NIH's AIDS program by Congress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg13818672-600-the-hour-of-the-activist-aids-campaigners-in-the-us-are-changing-the-way-the-nations-research-into-hiv-is-organised-will-other-diseases-get-the-same-treatment/|title=The hour of the activist: AIDS campaigners in the US are changing the way the nation's research into HIV is organised. Will other diseases get the same treatment?|last=Brown|first=Phyllida|website=New Scientist|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treatmentactiongroup.org/resources/tagline/tagline-spring-2012/tag-at-20-early-campaigns/|title=TAG at 20: Early Campaigns|website=Treatment Action Group|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>  He found out he was HIV+ in 1995.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sciencespeaksblog.org/2011/05/20/aids-at-30-an-interview-with-activist-gregg-gonsalves/|title=AIDS at 30: an interview with activist Gregg Gonsalves|date=May 20, 2011|work=Science Speaks: Global ID News|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> In 2000, Gonsalves went on to join [[Gay Men's Health Crisis]] and its Department of Public Policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poz.com/article/gregg-gonsalves-honored-hiv-14319-5887|title=AIDS Activist Gregg Gonsalves Honored|date=2008-03-27|website=POZ|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> In 2006, Gonsalves moved to Cape Town, South Africa to work for the [https://www.arasa.info/home/1 AIDS and Rights Alliance for Southern Africa] where he was part of campaigns to expand access to antiretroviral therapy in Southern Africa.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=khm-aaoSOGYC&pg=PA133&lpg=PA133&dq=gonsalves+south+africa+TAC+antiretroviral+literacy#v=onepage&q=gonsalves%20south%20africa%20TAC%20antiretroviral%20literacy&f=false|title=South African AIDS Activism and Global Health Politics|last=Mbali|first=M.|date=2013-03-29|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-31216-7|language=en}}</ref> In the mid-2000s, he gave well-regarded plenary speeches at two back-to-back International AIDS Conferences in Toronto and Mexico City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://actupny.org/reports/gonsalves_torontospeech.html|title=The ACT UP Historical Archive: Gonsalves speech: Reflecting Back and Looking Forward|website=actupny.org|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mykhalovskiy|first=Eric|last2=Brown|first2=Glen|last3=Kort|first3=Rodney|date=2009-10-06|title=XVII International AIDS Conference: From Evidence to Action - Social, behavioural and economic science and policy and political science|journal=Journal of the International AIDS Society|volume=12|issue=Suppl 1|pages=S5|doi=10.1186/1758-2652-12-S1-S5|issn=1758-2652|pmc=2759034|pmid=19811671}}</ref> He is also a co-founder of the [http://itpcglobal.org International Treatment Preparedness Coalition], a collective of AIDS activists from around the world fighting for access to AIDS treatment and other life-saving medicines through education, monitoring and advocacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://itpcglobal.org/|title=Home|website=ITPC|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> In 2008, he received $100,000 as the first recipient of the AIDS Leadership Award from the John M. Lloyd Foundation.<ref name=\"UN\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unaids.org/en/KnowledgeCentre/Resources/FeatureStories/archive/2008/20080509_gregg_gonsalves.asp |date=May 9, 2008 |publisher=[[UNAIDS]] |accessdate=November 4, 2010 |title=Leadership and AIDS: Gregg Gonsalves }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he enrolled in [[Yale College]] as part of the [[Eli Whitney Students Program]] and obtained a BS with distinction in Ecology and Evolutionary Biology in 2011. From 2011-2012, he was an [[Open Society Foundations]] Fellow comparing social movements on AIDS, tuberculosis and maternal health in South Africa, Brazil and Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensocietyfoundations.org/grants/open-society-fellowship?fellow=gregg-gonsalves|title=Open Society Fellowship|website=www.opensocietyfoundations.org|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> In 2012, he enrolled in a PhD program in the Epidemiology of Microbial Diseases at [[Yale School of Public Health]] and [[Yale Graduate School of Arts and Sciences]] obtaining a PhD in 2017, where he also co-founded the [https://law.yale.edu/ghjp Yale Global Health Justice Partnership], the first collaboration between the public health and law schools at Yale.[https://gsas.yale.edu/news/gregg-gonsalves-co-founds-law-schoolpublic-health-partnership]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.yale.edu/ghjp|title=Global Health Justice Partnership - Yale Law School|website=law.yale.edu|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> He writes regularly for the popular press and has contributed op-eds and articles to the New York Times, Washington Post, Foreign Policy and The Nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2014/10/28/stop-playing-cowboy-on-ebola/|title=Stop Playing Cowboy on Ebola|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/weve-got-to-act-up-to-stop-trumpcare/|title=We\u2019ve Got to ACT UP to Stop Trumpcare|date=2017-05-09|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/11/opinion/dont-weaken-the-fdas-drug-approval-process.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Don\u2019t Weaken the F.D.A.\u2019s Drug Approval Process|date=2015-06-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-22|last2=Harrington|first2=Mark|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Kessler|first3=David A.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/13/AR2011011303922.html|title=Gregg Gonsalves - Obama's zero-sum game in the fight against AIDS|date=2011-01-14|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/09/opinion/sunday/cure-hiv-aids.html|title=Opinion {{!}} This is Not A Cure for My H.I.V.|date=2019-03-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2019/02/08/us-really-could-end-aids-if-trump-administration-gets-out-way/|title=Perspective {{!}} The U.S. really could end AIDS \u2014 if the Trump administration gets out of the way|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|last2=|first2=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> He joined the faculty of Yale School of Public Health in July 2017. His research focuses on using quantitative models to improve the delivery of services and shape policy-making on HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg S.|last2=Copple|first2=J. Tyler|last3=Johnson|first3=Tyler|last4=Paltiel|first4=A. David|last5=Warren|first5=Joshua L.|date=2018-09-03|title=Bayesian adaptive algorithms for locating HIV mobile testing services|journal=BMC Medicine|volume=16|issue=1|pages=155|doi=10.1186/s12916-018-1129-0|issn=1741-7015|pmc=6120098|pmid=30173667}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg S|last2=Crawford|first2=Forrest W|date=2018-10-01|title=Dynamics of the HIV outbreak and response in Scott County, IN, USA, 2011\u201315: a modelling study|journal=The Lancet HIV|volume=5|issue=10|pages=e569\u2013e577|doi=10.1016/S2352-3018(18)30176-0|pmid=30220531|pmc=6192548|issn=2352-3018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|last2=Paltiel|first2=A.|last3=Cleary|first3=Paul|last4=Gill|first4=Michael|last5=Kitahata|first5=Mari|last6=Rebeiro|first6=Peter|last7=Silverberg|first7=Michael|last8=Horberg|first8=Michael|last9=Abraham|first9=Alison|last10=Althoff|first10=Keri|last11=Moore|first11=Richard|date=2017-08-15|title=A Flow-Based Model of the HIV Care Continuum in the United States|url=http://insights.ovid.com/|journal=Journal of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndromes|language=ENGLISH|volume=75|issue=5|pages=548\u2013553|doi=10.1097/QAI.0000000000001429|issn=1525-4135|pmid=28471841|pmc=5533168}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg S.|last2=Crawford|first2=Forrest W.|last3=Cleary|first3=Paul D.|last4=Kaplan|first4=Edward H.|last5=Paltiel|first5=A. David|date=2018-02-01|title=An Adaptive Approach to Locating Mobile HIV Testing Services|journal=Medical Decision Making|language=en|volume=38|issue=2|pages=262\u2013272|doi=10.1177/0272989X17716431|issn=0272-989X|pmc=5748375|pmid=28699382}}</ref> At Yale, he is affiliated with the Public Health Modeling Unit and the Yale Program in Addiction Medicine.[https://publichealth.yale.edu/modeling/][https://medicine.yale.edu/intmed/genmed/addictionmedicine/] In 2019, he received an ''Avenir'' award from the [[National Institute on Drug Abuse]], a grant program devoted \"to early-stage investigators who propose highly innovative studies [and] researchers who represent the future of addiction science\" for his proposal to examine the [[syndemic]] of HIV, hepatitis C and overdose in the contest of the US opioid crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/news-events/avenir-award-winners|title=Avenir Award Winners|last=Abuse|first=National Institute on Drug|date=2019-10-15|website=www.drugabuse.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nIn 2008, he won the [http://johnmlloyd.org John M. Lloyd Foundation]'s inaugural AIDS Leadership Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://johnmlloyd.org/archived-site-2007-2012/grant_programs_leadership.html|title=John M Lloyd Foundation|website=johnmlloyd.org|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>  In 2018, he was awarded a [[MacArthur Foundation]] [[MacArthur Fellows Program|\"Genius\" Fellowship]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nhregister.com/news/article/2-from-New-Haven-with-Yale-ties-win-625-000-13281844.php |title=2 from New Haven with Yale ties win $625,000 MacArthur 'genius' grants |first=Ed |last=Stannard |work=[[New Haven Register]] |date=October 5, 2018 |accessdate=October 12, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.macfound.org/fellows/1011/ |title=Gregg Gonsalves |publisher=MacArthur Foundation |date=October 5, 2018 |accessdate=October 12, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[LGBT people in science]]\n* [[List of Italian Americans]]\n* [[List of Portuguese Americans]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gonsalves, Gregg}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:People with HIV/AIDS]]\n[[Category:American health activists]]\n[[Category:MacArthur Fellows]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:Yale University faculty]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Gay academics]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American scientists of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists from the United States]]\n", "text_old": "'''Gregg Gonsalves''' is a global health activist, an epidemiologist, an Assistant Professor at [[Yale School of Public Health]] and an Associate Professor (adjunct) at [[Yale Law School]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://publichealth.yale.edu/people/gregg_gonsalves.profile |title=Gregg Gonsalves, PhD |publisher=[[Yale School of Public Health]] |access-date=July 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.yale.edu/gregg-gonsalves|title=Gregg Gonsalves - Yale Law School|website=law.yale.edu|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born in Mineola, New York on October 21, 1963, grew up in nearby East Meadow, NY and attended East Meadow High School.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://yalealumnimagazine.com/articles/4168-gregg-gonsalves |title=Its not just the germs |last=Shufro |first=Cathy |date=September\u2013October 2015 |work=Yale Alumni Magazine |access-date=July 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/long-island/gregg-gonsalves-macarthur-genius-1.21781209|title=Foundation honors LI native as 'genius'|website=Newsday|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> His parents were New York City school teachers, both of whom were born and grew up in Brooklyn, NY, with his father's family originally from Madeira, Portugal and his mother's family from Sicily, Italy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2018/10/04/654396763/a-global-health-evangelist-is-shocked-to-hear-hes-a-genius|title=A Global Health Evangelist Is Shocked To Hear He's A 'Genius'|last=Beaubien|first=Jason|date=October 4, 2018|website=NPR|language=en|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref> He attended [[Tufts University]] starting in 1981, but dropped out before finishing his BA degree in English and American Literature and Russian Language and Literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.tufts.edu/magazine/summer2004/features/feature4Sidebar.html|title=Tufts Magazine Archive Summer 2004|website=news.tufts.edu|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> He has two sisters, Carin Gonsalves, a physician in Philadelphia, and Dana Gonsalves, a commercial artist in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hospitals.jefferson.edu/find-a-doctor/g/gonsalves-carin-f.html|title=Carin F. Gonsalves, MD - Jefferson University Hospitals|website=hospitals.jefferson.edu|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sequelstudio.com/views/spotlight-gonsalves|title=\"How lucky am I? I get to spend my days doing what I love to do \u2014 designing with a purpose, bringing together great storytelling and design.\" {{!}} Sequel|website=sequelstudio.com|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><!--Article from 2015 gives age as 51 -->\n\n== Career ==\nHe began working with the AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power ([[ACT UP]]) in 1990, going on to co-found the [[Treatment Action Group]] (TAG) in 1992, with his colleagues from the Treatment and Data Committee of ACT UP New York, including [[Peter Staley]], [[Mark Harrington (HIV/AIDS activist)|Mark Harrington]], [[Spencer Cox (activist)|Spencer Cox]]. With TAG, he authored several reports on HIV research, including a critical review of AIDS research at the [[National Institutes of Health]], which led to a reorganization of the NIH's AIDS program by Congress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg13818672-600-the-hour-of-the-activist-aids-campaigners-in-the-us-are-changing-the-way-the-nations-research-into-hiv-is-organised-will-other-diseases-get-the-same-treatment/|title=The hour of the activist: AIDS campaigners in the US are changing the way the nation's research into HIV is organised. Will other diseases get the same treatment?|last=Brown|first=Phyllida|website=New Scientist|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treatmentactiongroup.org/resources/tagline/tagline-spring-2012/tag-at-20-early-campaigns/|title=TAG at 20: Early Campaigns|website=Treatment Action Group|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>  He found out he was HIV+ in 1995.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sciencespeaksblog.org/2011/05/20/aids-at-30-an-interview-with-activist-gregg-gonsalves/|title=AIDS at 30: an interview with activist Gregg Gonsalves|date=May 20, 2011|work=Science Speaks: Global ID News|access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> In 2000, Gonsalves went on to join [[Gay Men's Health Crisis]] and its Department of Public Policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poz.com/article/gregg-gonsalves-honored-hiv-14319-5887|title=AIDS Activist Gregg Gonsalves Honored|date=2008-03-27|website=POZ|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> In 2006, Gonsalves moved to Cape Town, South Africa to work for the [https://www.arasa.info/home/1 AIDS and Rights Alliance for Southern Africa] where he was part of campaigns to expand access to antiretroviral therapy in Southern Africa.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=khm-aaoSOGYC&pg=PA133&lpg=PA133&dq=gonsalves+south+africa+TAC+antiretroviral+literacy#v=onepage&q=gonsalves%20south%20africa%20TAC%20antiretroviral%20literacy&f=false|title=South African AIDS Activism and Global Health Politics|last=Mbali|first=M.|date=2013-03-29|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-31216-7|language=en}}</ref> In the mid-2000s, he gave well-regarded plenary speeches at two back-to-back International AIDS Conferences in Toronto and Mexico City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://actupny.org/reports/gonsalves_torontospeech.html|title=The ACT UP Historical Archive: Gonsalves speech: Reflecting Back and Looking Forward|website=actupny.org|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mykhalovskiy|first=Eric|last2=Brown|first2=Glen|last3=Kort|first3=Rodney|date=2009-10-06|title=XVII International AIDS Conference: From Evidence to Action - Social, behavioural and economic science and policy and political science|journal=Journal of the International AIDS Society|volume=12|issue=Suppl 1|pages=S5|doi=10.1186/1758-2652-12-S1-S5|issn=1758-2652|pmc=2759034|pmid=19811671}}</ref> He is also a co-founder of the [http://itpcglobal.org International Treatment Preparedness Coalition], a collective of AIDS activists from around the world fighting for access to AIDS treatment and other life-saving medicines through education, monitoring and advocacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://itpcglobal.org/|title=Home|website=ITPC|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> In 2008, he received $100,000 as the first recipient of the AIDS Leadership Award from the John M. Lloyd Foundation.<ref name=\"UN\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unaids.org/en/KnowledgeCentre/Resources/FeatureStories/archive/2008/20080509_gregg_gonsalves.asp |date=May 9, 2008 |publisher=[[UNAIDS]] |accessdate=November 4, 2010 |title=Leadership and AIDS: Gregg Gonsalves }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he enrolled in [[Yale College]] as part of the [[Eli Whitney Students Program]] and obtained a BS with distinction in Ecology and Evolutionary Biology in 2011. From 2011-2012, he was an [[Open Society Foundations]] Fellow comparing social movements on AIDS, tuberculosis and maternal health in South Africa, Brazil and Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensocietyfoundations.org/grants/open-society-fellowship?fellow=gregg-gonsalves|title=Open Society Fellowship|website=www.opensocietyfoundations.org|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> In 2012, he enrolled in a PhD program in the Epidemiology of Microbial Diseases at [[Yale School of Public Health]] and [[Yale Graduate School of Arts and Sciences]] obtaining a PhD in 2017, where he also co-founded the [https://law.yale.edu/ghjp Yale Global Health Justice Partnership], the first collaboration between the public health and law schools at Yale.[https://gsas.yale.edu/news/gregg-gonsalves-co-founds-law-schoolpublic-health-partnership]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.yale.edu/ghjp|title=Global Health Justice Partnership - Yale Law School|website=law.yale.edu|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> He writes regularly for the popular press and has contributed op-eds and articles to the New York Times, Washington Post, Foreign Policy and The Nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2014/10/28/stop-playing-cowboy-on-ebola/|title=Stop Playing Cowboy on Ebola|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/weve-got-to-act-up-to-stop-trumpcare/|title=We\u2019ve Got to ACT UP to Stop Trumpcare|date=2017-05-09|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/11/opinion/dont-weaken-the-fdas-drug-approval-process.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Don\u2019t Weaken the F.D.A.\u2019s Drug Approval Process|date=2015-06-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-22|last2=Harrington|first2=Mark|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Kessler|first3=David A.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/13/AR2011011303922.html|title=Gregg Gonsalves - Obama's zero-sum game in the fight against AIDS|date=2011-01-14|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/09/opinion/sunday/cure-hiv-aids.html|title=Opinion {{!}} This is Not A Cure for My H.I.V.|date=2019-03-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2019/02/08/us-really-could-end-aids-if-trump-administration-gets-out-way/|title=Perspective {{!}} The U.S. really could end AIDS \u2014 if the Trump administration gets out of the way|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|last2=|first2=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> He joined the faculty of Yale School of Public Health in July 2017. His research focuses on using quantitative models to improve the delivery of services and shape policy-making on HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg S.|last2=Copple|first2=J. Tyler|last3=Johnson|first3=Tyler|last4=Paltiel|first4=A. David|last5=Warren|first5=Joshua L.|date=2018-09-03|title=Bayesian adaptive algorithms for locating HIV mobile testing services|journal=BMC Medicine|volume=16|issue=1|pages=155|doi=10.1186/s12916-018-1129-0|issn=1741-7015|pmc=6120098|pmid=30173667}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg S|last2=Crawford|first2=Forrest W|date=2018-10-01|title=Dynamics of the HIV outbreak and response in Scott County, IN, USA, 2011\u201315: a modelling study|journal=The Lancet HIV|volume=5|issue=10|pages=e569\u2013e577|doi=10.1016/S2352-3018(18)30176-0|pmid=30220531|pmc=6192548|issn=2352-3018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg|last2=Paltiel|first2=A.|last3=Cleary|first3=Paul|last4=Gill|first4=Michael|last5=Kitahata|first5=Mari|last6=Rebeiro|first6=Peter|last7=Silverberg|first7=Michael|last8=Horberg|first8=Michael|last9=Abraham|first9=Alison|last10=Althoff|first10=Keri|last11=Moore|first11=Richard|date=2017-08-15|title=A Flow-Based Model of the HIV Care Continuum in the United States|url=http://insights.ovid.com/|journal=Journal of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndromes|language=ENGLISH|volume=75|issue=5|pages=548\u2013553|doi=10.1097/QAI.0000000000001429|issn=1525-4135|pmid=28471841|pmc=5533168}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gonsalves|first=Gregg S.|last2=Crawford|first2=Forrest W.|last3=Cleary|first3=Paul D.|last4=Kaplan|first4=Edward H.|last5=Paltiel|first5=A. David|date=2018-02-01|title=An Adaptive Approach to Locating Mobile HIV Testing Services|journal=Medical Decision Making|language=en|volume=38|issue=2|pages=262\u2013272|doi=10.1177/0272989X17716431|issn=0272-989X|pmc=5748375|pmid=28699382}}</ref> At Yale, he is affiliated with the Public Health Modeling Unit and the Yale Program in Addiction Medicine.[https://publichealth.yale.edu/modeling/][https://medicine.yale.edu/intmed/genmed/addictionmedicine/] In 2019, he received an ''Avenir'' award from the [[National Institute on Drug Abuse]], a grant program devoted \"to early-stage investigators who propose highly innovative studies [and] researchers who represent the future of addiction science\" for his proposal to examine the [[syndemic]] of HIV, hepatitis C and overdose in the contest of the US opioid crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.drugabuse.gov/news-events/avenir-award-winners|title=Avenir Award Winners|last=Abuse|first=National Institute on Drug|date=2019-10-15|website=www.drugabuse.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honors ==\nIn 2008, he won the [http://johnmlloyd.org John M. Lloyd Foundation]'s inaugural AIDS Leadership Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://johnmlloyd.org/archived-site-2007-2012/grant_programs_leadership.html|title=John M Lloyd Foundation|website=johnmlloyd.org|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>  2018, he was awarded a [[MacArthur Foundation]] [[MacArthur Fellows Program|\"Genius\" Fellowship]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nhregister.com/news/article/2-from-New-Haven-with-Yale-ties-win-625-000-13281844.php |title=2 from New Haven with Yale ties win $625,000 MacArthur 'genius' grants |first=Ed |last=Stannard |work=[[New Haven Register]] |date=October 5, 2018 |accessdate=October 12, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.macfound.org/fellows/1011/ |title=Gregg Gonsalves |publisher=MacArthur Foundation |date=October 5, 2018 |accessdate=October 12, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[LGBT people in science]]\n* [[List of Italian Americans]]\n* [[List of Portuguese Americans]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gonsalves, Gregg}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:People with HIV/AIDS]]\n[[Category:American health activists]]\n[[Category:MacArthur Fellows]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:Yale University faculty]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Gay academics]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American scientists of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists from the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Mkcabby", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregg_Gonsalves"}
{"title_page": "Politics and technology", "text_new": "{{Politics}}\n\nThe combination of '''politics and technology''' covers concepts, mechanisms, personalities, efforts, and [[social movement]]s including but not necessarily limited to the [[Internet]] and other [[Information technology|information and communication technologies]] (ICTs).\n\nA growing body of scholarship has begun to explore how Internet technologies are influencing [[political communication]] and [[Participation (decision making)|participation]], especially in terms of what is known as the [[public sphere]].\n\nOne of the most influential and transformational information and communication technologies is the [[mobile phone]] or [[smartphone]], which can include: talk, text messaging, [[Internet]] and [[World Wide Web|Web]] access, [[electronic mail]], [[faxing]], pictures, video, and a wide variety of [[Mobile app|apps]]. Mobile devices are proving to increase political participation and are now even being portrayed as a voting gadget in even the [[least developed countries]]. Increased availability of this [[technology]] and subsequent access to the public sphere has enhanced the ability of individuals and groups to bring attention to and organize around specialized issues.<ref>Creeber, Glen. Digital Cultures: [understanding New Media]. Maidenhead: Open Univ., 2009. Print.</ref>\n\nMore recently, [[social media]] has emerged to become one of the main areas of influence for [[politics]], where millions of users are able to learn about politicians' policies and statements, interact with political leaders, organize, and voice their own opinions on political matters.<ref>{{cite book|title=Politics and the Twitter revolution : how tweets influence the relationship between political leaders and the public|last2=Bichard|first2=Shannon|date=2012|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=9780739165010|location=Lanham, MD|page=1|last1=Parmelee|first1=John}}</ref> For instance, the influence of mainstream rappers like Stormzy, Professor Green and Kano, on young voters through the use of social media. In the 2017 election the spike in youth turnout changed political analysis, with age replacing class for the first time as the best predictor of voting intention. In the 2019 election, of 18-25 year olds 56% voted Labour and 21% Conservative. Although this cannot ever be wholly contributed to the backing of Corbyn by young influencers, the effect cannot be underestimated. In a letter to the Guardian, put together by the Grime4Corbyn movement, many artists urge voters to back Labour to \u201cend austerity, rebuild our communities and take back the means to change our lives for the better\u201d. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/25/stormzy-backs-labour-in-election-with-call-to-end-austerity|title=Stormzy backs Labour in election with call to end austerity|last=Gayle|first=Damien|date=2019-11-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>Securing the backing of Stormzy, one of the UK\u2019s biggest recording artists, is a major coup for the Labour party and after lending his support in 2017, Stormzy was credited in part for the \u201cyouthquake\u201d that boosted Corbyn\u2019s party in that year\u2019s election. \n\nThere are also a wide variety of online tools that are meant to promote political participation and combat the spread of misinformation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paularmstrongtech/2018/03/01/how-technology-is-really-going-to-change-politics-in-the-next-20-years/|title=How Technology Is Really Going To Change Politics In The Next 20 Years|last=Armstrong|first=Paul|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> A [[comparison of civic technology platforms]] can be useful in differentiating the different services offered by each platform.\n\n== The digital public sphere ==\nThe idea of the [[public sphere]] has generally come to be understood as the open social spaces and [[public space]]s in which private citizens interact and share information and ideas relevant to the society. These can include, for example, town halls, public squares, markets, coffee shops, or what ancient Greeks called [[agora]]s. Many scholars have argued that these spaces are vitally important for creating and maintaining an active and informed public in a democratic society.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/freespaces00sara|title=Free spaces : the sources of democratic change in America|last=Evans|first=Sara M.|last2=Boyte|first2=Harry C.|date=1992|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0226222578|edition=2nd|location=Chicago|pages=|oclc=24669015}}</ref>\n\nIn [[J\u00fcrgen Habermas]]' book  ''[[The Structural Transformation of the Public Sphere|The Structural Transformation of the Public Sphere \u2013 An Inquiry into a Category of Bourgeois Society]]'', he defines the public sphere as \"a realm of social life in which public opinion can be formed.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The structural transformation of the public sphere : an inquiry into a category of bourgeois society|last=J\u00fcrgen|first=Habermas|publisher=|year=1962|isbn=978-0262081801|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=|oclc=18327374}}</ref> In principle, the public sphere should be open to all citizens, and free from influence from governments or private businesses. Habermas goes on to argue that:<blockquote href=\"Digital rights\">\"A portion of the public sphere is constituted in every conversation in which private persons come together to form a public. They are then acting neither as business or professional people conducting their private affairs, nor as legal consociates subject to the legal regulations of a state bureaucracy and obligated to obedience. Citizens act as a public when they deal with matters of general interest without being subject to coercion; thus with the guarantee that they may assemble and unite freely, and express and publicize their opinions freely.\"<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>[[Howard Rheingold]] argues that, \"There is an intimate connection between informal conversations, the kind that take place in communities... and the ability of large social groups to govern themselves without monarchs or dictators.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The virtual community : homesteading on the electronic frontier|last=Howard.|first=Rheingold|date=2000|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0262681216|edition= Rev. |location=Cambridge, Mass.|oclc=44162557}}</ref> Rheingold and others<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dahlgren|first=Peter|date=2006|title=The Internet, Public Spheres, and Political Communication: Dispersion and Deliberation|journal=Political Communication|volume=22|issue=2|pages=147\u2013162|doi=10.1080/10584600590933160}}</ref> have also gone on to argue that virtual spaces created through the [[Internet]] and related [[Information and communications technology|information and communications technologies]] have led to the emergence of a new type of digital public sphere. Some scholars have conceptualized this alternately as a virtual public sphere<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Papacharissi|first=Zizi|date=2002|title=The virtual sphere|journal=New Media & Society|language=en|volume=4|issue=1|pages=9\u201327|doi=10.1177/14614440222226244|issn=1461-4448}}</ref> or a networked public sphere,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shirky|first=Clay|date=2011|title=The Political Power of Social Media: Technology, the Public Sphere, and Political Change|jstor=25800379|journal=Foreign Affairs|volume=90|issue=1|pages=28\u201341}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Twitter and tear gas : the power and fragility of networked protest|last=Zeynep|first=Tufekci|publisher=|year=2017|isbn=9780300215120|location=New Haven|pages=|oclc=961312425}}</ref> while still others have similarly described what they call a networked society<ref>{{Cite book|title=Communication power|last=Castells|first=Manuel|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2013|isbn=9780191510434|edition= 2nd|location=Oxford|pages=|oclc=855022865}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Networks of outrage and hope: social movements in the Internet age|last=Castells|first=Manuel|publisher=Polity|year=2015|isbn=9780745662855|edition= 2nd|location=Cambridge|pages=|oclc=795757037}}</ref> or networked publics.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Networked Publics|last=Varnelis|first=Kazys|publisher=MIT Press|others=Annenberg Center for Communication (University of Southern California)|year=2008|isbn=9780262285483|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=|oclc=283798198}}</ref> Essentially, these new virtual spaces can be used in much the same way as traditional, offline spaces; that is, as a \"free space\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Democratic phoenix : reinventing political activism|last=Pippa|first=Norris|date=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0521811774|location=Cambridge, UK|pages=|oclc=48943689}}</ref> to discuss and debate ideas of public importance. Just as the public sphere is a combination of \"every conversation in which private persons come together to form a public\"<ref name=\":0\" /> the digital public sphere also comprises all forms of [[new media]], such as [[chat room]]s, website comment sections, and [[social media]], in which private citizens engage in discourse as a public. Virtual spaces may overlap or interact with offline spaces as well, forming what has been called \"hybrid networks\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lim|first=Merlyna|date=2015|title=A CyberUrban Space Odyssey: The Spatiality of Contemporary Social Movements|url=https://www.academia.edu/16240525|journal=New Geographies|language=en|volume=7|pages=117\u2013123|via=}}</ref>\n\nMany scholars argue that social media affords increasing opportunities for political discourse and mobilization within the digital public sphere.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Loader|first=Brian D.|last2=Mercea|first2=Dan|date=2011|title=Networking Democracy? Social media innovations and participatory politics|journal=Information, Communication & Society|volume=14|issue=6|pages=757\u2013769|doi=10.1080/1369118X.2011.592648|url=http://openaccess.city.ac.uk/5528/1/Networking%20Democracy%20iCS%20Intro%2014%206%20%28amended%29.pdf}}</ref> Research has shown that increased use of social media correlates with increases in certain types of political engagement and [[Participation (decision making)|participation]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boulianne|first=Shelly|year=2015|title=Social media use and participation: a meta-analysis of current research|journal=Information, Communication & Society|volume=18|issue=5|pages=524\u2013538|doi=10.1080/1369118X.2015.1008542}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kahne|first=Joseph|last2=Bowyer|first2=Benjamin|date=2018|title=The Political Significance of Social Media Activity and Social Networks|journal=Political Communication|volume=35|issue=3|pages=470\u2013493|doi=10.1080/10584609.2018.1426662}}</ref> The digital public sphere thus has the potential to enliven democratic culture<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/viralspiralhowco0000boll|title=Viral spiral : how the commoners built a digital republic of their own|last=David.|first=Bollier|date=2008|publisher=New Press|isbn=978-1595583963|location=New York|oclc=227016731}}</ref> and enhance the ability of citizens to challenge the political and economic power of governments and corporations<ref name=\":1\" /> such as through online [[protest]]s, [[activism]] campaigns, and [[social movement]]s.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Digitally enabled social change : activism in the Internet age|last=Earl|first=Jennifer|last2=Kimport|first2=Katrina|publisher=MIT Press|year=2011|isbn=9780262015103|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=|oclc=639573767}}</ref> Other scholars have also highlighted, alongside [[economic globalization]], the role of Internet technologies to reach across national borders to contribute to a growing transnational public sphere.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.press.umich.edu/11707|title=Globalizations and Social Movements|date=2000|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=9780472097210|editor-last=Guidry|editor-first=John|location=Ann Arbor, MI|language=en|doi=10.3998/mpub.11707|editor-last2=Kennedy|editor-first2=Michael|editor-last3=Zald|editor-first3=Mayer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Transnational activism in Asia : problems of power and democracy|last=Piper|first=Nicola|last2=Uhlin|first2=Anders|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|isbn=978-0415315135|location=London|pages=|oclc=51817597}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms ==\n\n==== Social exclusion ====\nThe traditional, offline public sphere has been criticized for not being as inclusive in practice as it is in theory.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Habermas and the public sphere|last=|first=|publisher=MIT Press|year=1992|isbn=978-0262031837|editor-last=Calhoun|editor-first=Craig J.|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=|oclc=23650367}}</ref> For example, Feminist scholars like [[Nancy Fraser]] have argued that the public sphere has historically not been as open or accessible to [[Social exclusion|disadvantaged or marginalized groups]] in a society, such as women or people of color; therefore, such groups are forced to form their own separate public spheres, which she refers to as a ''counter-public'' or ''subaltern counter public'' (see {{slink|Public sphere#Counterpublics, feminist critiques and expansions}}).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fraser|first=Nancy|date=1990|title=Rethinking the Public Sphere: A Contribution to the Critique of Actually Existing Democracy|jstor=466240|journal=Social Text|issue=25/26|pages=56\u201380|doi=10.2307/466240}}</ref>\n\nSome scholars contend that online spaces are more open and thus may help to increase inclusive political participation from marginalized groups.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schlosberg|first=David|last2=Dryzek|first2=John S.|date=2002|title=Digital Democracy: Authentic or Virtual?|jstor=26162195|journal=Organization & Environment|volume=15|issue=3|pages=332\u2013335|doi=10.1177/1086026602153011}}</ref> In particular, [[Anonymity|anonymous]] online spaces should allow all individuals to speak with an equal voice to others.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Deseriis|first=M.|date=2013|title=Is Anonymous a New Form of Luddism?: A Comparative Analysis of Industrial Machine Breaking, Computer Hacking, and Related Rhetorical Strategies|journal=Radical History Review|language=en|volume=2013|issue=117|pages=33\u201348|doi=10.1215/01636545-2210437|issn=0163-6545}}</ref> However, other have pointed out that many contemporary online spaces are not anonymous, such as [[Facebook]]. Avatars and social media profiles often portray an individual's offline identity, which can lead to practices of online discrimination and exclusion which mirror offline inequalities.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Digitizing race : visual cultures of the Internet|last=Lisa|first=Nakamura|date=2008|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|isbn=9780816653775|location=Minneapolis|pages=|oclc=214085023}}</ref> Now, more and more historically disadvantaged or marginalized groups are also using Internet technology to carve out new online spaces for their own \"networked counterpublics\" such as through the use of [[hashtag]]s like #Ferguson and [[Black Lives Matter|#BlackLivesMatter]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jackson|first=Sarah J.|last2=Foucault Welles|first2=Brooke|date=2015|title=Hijacking #myNYPD: Social Media Dissent and Networked Counterpublics|journal=Journal of Communication|language=en|volume=65|issue=6|pages=932\u2013952|doi=10.1111/jcom.12185|issn=0021-9916}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jackson|first=Sarah J.|last2=Foucault Welles|first2=Brooke|date=2016|title=#Ferguson is everywhere: initiators in emerging counterpublic networks|journal=Information, Communication & Society|volume=19|issue=3|pages=397\u2013418|doi=10.1080/1369118X.2015.1106571}}</ref>\n\n==== The digital divide ====\nAnother factor which affects access to the digital public sphere is the [[digital divide]], which refers to how people from [[Least Developed Countries|less developed countries]] tend to have less access to [[Information and communications technology|information and communications technologies]] compared to those from more [[Developed country|developed countries]]. For example, the most developed regions of the world, such as North America and Western Europe, have the highest [[Global Internet usage|Internet penetration rates]] at over 80% each, while the least developed countries such as in Africa and South Asia have less than 30% each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/269329/penetration-rate-of-the-internet-by-region/|title=Global regional internet penetration rate 2017 {{!}} Statistic|website=Statista|language=en|access-date=2018-07-01}}</ref> On the other hand, the reduced cost and increasing availability of mobile devices such as [[smartphone]]s throughout less developed regions is helping to reduce this disparity at an exponential rate. In just two years, between 2013 and 2015, the number of Internet users in developing nations has risen by 9%, according to the [[Pew Research Center]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2016/02/22/smartphone-ownership-and-internet-usage-continues-to-climb-in-emerging-economies/|title=Smartphone Ownership and Internet Usage Continues to Climb in Emerging Economies|date=2016-02-22|work=Pew Research Center's Global Attitudes Project|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Other research has shown, though, that even within more developed countries like the United States, the digital divide continues to persist between upper and lower socioeconomic classes<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brookings.edu/research/broadband-adoption-rates-and-gaps-in-u-s-metropolitan-areas/|title=Broadband adoption rates and gaps in U.S. metropolitan areas|last=Tomer|first=Adie|date=2015|work=Brookings|access-date=2018-07-01|last2=Kane|first2=Joseph|language=en-US}}</ref> and between different education levels.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/03/05/some-americans-dont-use-the-internet-who-are-they/|title=11% of Americans don't use the internet. Who are they?|date=2018-03-05|work=Pew Research Center|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Furthermore, scholars like [[Mark Warschauer]] argue that it is not just access to technology that matters, but the knowledge of how to put that technology to use in meaningful ways.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Technology and social inclusion : rethinking the digital divide|last=Mark.|first=Warschauer|date=2003|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0262232241|location=Cambridge, Mass.|oclc=50028800|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/technologysocial0000wars}}</ref>\n\n==== Use of Bots and Sock Puppets ====\nInternet bots, also known as a web robot, robot or simply bot, is a software application that runs automated tasks (scripts) over the Internet.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guenon des Mesnards|first=Nicolas|title=Detecting Influence Campaigns in Social Networks Using the Ising Model|journal=|volume=|pages=|arxiv=1805.10244|year=2018|bibcode=2018arXiv180510244G}}</ref> Typically, bots perform tasks that are both simple and structurally repetitive, at a much higher rate than would be possible for a human alone. The largest use of bots is in web spidering, in which an automated script fetches, analyzes and files information from web servers at many times the speed of a human. More than half of all web traffic is made up of bots. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/terms/web_crawler.htm|title=Web crawler|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> This aids in the detection of bots as through qualitative coding, softwares can confirm the presence of bots. An example would be the Bot-a-meter developed by Indiana University, where they evaluate 7 different factors to determine whether or not an accounts is a bot. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://botometer.iuni.iu.edu/|title=Botometer by OSoMe|website=botometer.iuni.iu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> \n\nA Sock Puppet is an online identity used for purposes of deception<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2127107-sock-puppet-accounts-unmasked-by-the-way-they-write-and-post/|website=www.newscientist.com|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>. The term originally referred to a false identity assumed by a member of an Internet community who is pretending to be another person. This includes other misleading uses of online identities, such as those created to praise, defend or support a person or organization, to manipulate public opinion, block evasion, ballot stuffing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/opinion/our_view/our-view-bots-and-sockpuppets-are-deepening-the-political-divide/article_31fbbd42-1745-11e8-baec-db909ca5572d.html|title=Our View: Bots and sockpuppets are deepening the political divide|website=PostBulletin.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>. There is significant evidence to indicate that the [[Internet Research Agency]], a group of professional Russian Trolls, created fake accounts on major networking sites, online newspapers, to promote specific Ukrainian, Middle Eastern, and American political issues, even advocating for Trump as early as December 2015. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/feb/23/troll-steven-poole-word-of-week|title=What's the difference between a troll and a sockpuppet?|last=Poole|first=Steven|date=2018-02-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Leapfrog Democracies ==\n[[File:Estonian municipal elections 2013.png|thumb|This is the divide of the different political parties in Estonia where in the 2013 elections, over 133,000 people (roughly 21.2% of participating voters) voted over the Internet. The 2013 elections  were also the first elections to allow vote verification with mobile devices. ]]\nLeapfrog democracies<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iftf.org/future-now/article-detail/leapfrog-democracies-personal-democracy-forum/|title=IFTF: Leapfrog Democracies @ Personal Democracy Forum|website=www.iftf.org|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> developed in the field of industrial organization and economic growth. It was a term first used at the Personal Democracy Forum in 2014. The basic concept of [[leapfrogging]] is that small and incremental innovations lead allow radical innovations with new firms or countries to \"leapfrog\" old and ancient ones, including with different governmental institutions and ideas. Countries that have huge developments that more typically advanced countries might only have much later. \n\n==== Tunisia ====\nAn example of this is the new [[Tunisia|Tunsia]] constitution. Learning from America and other countries, Tunisia developed a constitution that provides more rights that typical constitutions with issues concerning climate change, healthcare, women's rights, and workers' rights. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thinkprogress.org/4-ways-tunisia-is-now-more-progressive-than-the-united-states-9879ae93d105/|title=4 Ways Tunisia Is Now More Progressive Than The United States|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> They have provided rights that the United States' government does not cover for its citizens. Tunisia has set the stage for many other countries to follow in their footsteps including Egypt, Libya, Yemen, and Syria. Although these countries' attempts at democracies have not been nearly as successful as Tunisia's constitution. \n\n==== Estonia ====\nAnother example of a Leapfrog democracy is Estonia being one of the first countries to use online voting. Nearly 99% of their public services are available online, and a reported 44% of Estonia citizens use the online services. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://e-estonia.com/solutions/e-governance/i-voting/|title=i-Voting|website=e-Estonia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> [[Electronic voting in Estonia|Electronic Voting in Estonia]] has been occurring since 2005 and can cast votes through an app on their mobile device. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kalevleetaru/2017/06/07/how-estonias-e-voting-system-could-be-the-future/|title=How Estonia's E-Voting System Could Be The Future|last=Leetaru|first=Kalev|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> Through Estonia's national ID infrastructure, National ID cards have the ability to perform cryptographic functions to authenticate their access to different websites and make legally binding signatures on documents if needed. These cards work through the use of two different RSA key pairs. However, there are still some drawbacks of this voting process as there are inadequate procedural controls that change several times or are not followed, lax operational security, and insufficient transparency. These weaknesses can allow for client side attacks on the voting system.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Springall|first=Drew|chapter=Security Analysis of the Estonian Internet Voting System|title= CCS '14: Proceedings of the 2014 ACM SIGSAC Conference on Computer and Communications Security |year=2014|pages=703\u2013715|doi=10.1145/2660267.2660315|isbn=9781450329576}}</ref>\n\n== Presence of online tools for political participation ==\n\nWith the increasing use of technology in the political sphere, many new platforms have emerged in an attempt to provide unbiased information to the general public in a manner that is easy access to all. The idea of spreading unbiased information has become a popular platform for many apps to get started on. Many of these apps hope to be able to spread this information so that voters may be more educated about the political sphere and make more of an informed decision when voting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paularmstrongtech/2018/03/01/how-technology-is-really-going-to-change-politics-in-the-next-20-years/|title=How Technology Is Really Going To Change Politics In The Next 20 Years|last=Armstrong|first=Paul|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> Some more examples include Liquid.us, Countable<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.countable.us/|title=Contact your Reps, Influence Congress, Vote on Bills|website=www.countable.us|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>, Capitol Bells<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.capitolbells.com/splash/|title=Capitol Bells|website=www.capitolbells.com|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>, Fiscalnote<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fiscalnote.com/|title=Homepage|website=FiscalNote|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>, and Councilmatic<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://councilmatic.org/|title=Councilmatic - Your local city council, demystified|last=Councilmatic|website=Councilmatic|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. Technology is progressing rapidly to making a significant impact on our future campaigns. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iop.harvard.edu/get-involved/study-groups/technology-innovation-and-politics-led-sonal-shah|title=Technology, Innovation and Politics led by Sonal Shah|website=The Institute of Politics at Harvard University|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> A [[comparison of civic technology platforms]] highlights the similarities and differences between different online tools used for political participation. \n\n==== PopVox ====\nAn example of this is PopVox, as they provide a holistic view of every bill and resolution that has passed or is currently in discussion with our government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popvox.com/|title=Your direct connection to lawmakers|website=www.popvox.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> Popvox also provides a platform for voters to share their opinions on different bills being discussed in Congress at the moment, and from the start of the app over 350,000 people have used the app from across the country to share their opinions on bills and become more informed. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/sarahmckinney/2014/02/01/the-future-of-political-engagement-is-here-and-its-called-popvox/|title=The Future Of Political Engagement Is Here (And It's Called POPVOX)|last=McKinney|first=Sarah|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n==== iSideWith ====\niSideWith is an application that seeks to provide voters with a more educated guess of who they would politically side with<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isidewith.com/|title=America's most popular voting guide for elections, political issues, candidates, and poll data|website=iSideWith|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. They have an in-depth survey on their website that asks about the users' political opinion on common issues discussed or debated within the government currently to give the voter a ranking of which politician best aligns with what stance they have on the current political sphere<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isidewith.com/political-quiz|title=2019 Political Quiz|website=iSideWith|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>. This gives voters more of an educated guess of who they should be casting their vote for. The more time the voters spend filling out the survey, the more accurate the results will align with their political stance. \n\n==== Change.org ====\n[[File:Change.org.jpg|thumb|The logo and slogan for change.org]]\nChange.org is a website that allows for people to take a stance on something they agree or disagree with and actually petition for others to rally behind their cause<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.activistfacts.com/organizations/530-change-dot-org/|title=Change.org {{!}} Funding sources, staff profiles, and political agenda {{!}} Activist FactsActivist Facts|website=Activist Facts|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>. People can search up petitions that have been started already concerning a cause that they may feel strongly about or they have the option of starting their own. The website displays past successful petitions that have made an impact and the petition does not necessarily have to be related to politics as well. There are many different surveys started by different people that could just be targeting different issues within their neighborhood but can range up to a social issue that they believe the whole world should be aware about. \n\n==== D21 ====\nD21 is a platform that allows people to participate in voting on issues through a form of \"modern democracy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.d21.me/|title=D21 {{!}} Participation and voting in municipalities, schools and companies.|website=en.d21.me|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> It is also known as the Jane\u010dek Method which allows people to cast both a negative and a positive vote<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cmu.edu/news/stories/archives/2016/march/better-way-for-voters.html|title=Alumnus Gives Voters A Better Way to Decide - News - Carnegie Mellon University|last=University|first=Carnegie Mellon|date=2016|website=www.cmu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. They wish to inform users more accurately about different issues happening within their community and provide them with a platform for them to be able to voice their opinions on. This is a platform that is used mainly in the Czech Republic to target corruption within the Czech government. Though it has not yet been used in any general elections, the Jane\u010dek Method has been used in several participatory budgeting programs around the world, including  New York City in the United States<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civichall.org/civicist/new-york-city-tests-digital-ballot-in-participatory-budget-vote/|title=New York City Tests Digital Ballot in Participatory Budget Vote|website=Civic Hall|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. The Czech government introduced the game Prezident 21 which is an interactive website created to aid people in familiarizing themselves with the D21 system<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prezident21.cz/|title=Prezident 21|last=www.benes-michl.cz|first=Bene\u0161 & Michl|website=www.prezident21.cz|language=cs|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>.  \n\n==== Verified Voting ====\nVerified Voting is a website uses its online presence to discourage the movement of voting towards the more digital age. Specifically having a section about Internet Voting, they speak about the dangers and information leaks that come with using the internet or anything digital to cast votes, even with blockchain. Verified Voting defines internet voting to even include email or fax voting or any voting through an online portal. This is due to the fact that any form of electronic voting can cause the vote to be susceptible to a large number of security threats including cyber-attacks that can skew voting results and preferences<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verifiedvoting.org/resources/internet-voting/|title=Internet Voting {{!}} Verified Voting|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. According to NIST, it is difficult to make sure that votes are coming from verified and registered voters and it has not been changed in transit. This is difficult to verify over the internet and thus makes casting votes in person and through paper ballets more effective and safe, even with the flaws that it may have<ref>{{Cite document|last=Regenscheid|first=Andrew|last2=Hastings|first2=Nelson|title=A Threat Analysis on UOCAVA Voting Systems|year=2008|url=https://www.nist.gov/system/files/documents/itl/vote/uocava-threatanalysis-final.pdf|id=NISTIR 7551|pages=78|publisher=NIST|doi=10.6028/NIST.IR.7551}}</ref>.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[:Category:Regulation of technologies]]\n* [[Cultural lag]]\n* [[Digital rights]]\n* [[E-democracy]]\n* [[E-government]]\n* [[Electronic voting]]\n* [[Hashtag activism]]\n* [[Internet activism]]\n* [[Internet censorship]]\n* [[Media activism]]\n* [[Neo-Luddism]]\n* [[Netizen]]\n* [[Online deliberation]]\n* [[Public hypersphere]]\n* [[Technocracy]]\n* [[Technology policy]]\n* [[Comparison of civic technology platforms]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Politics by issue|Technology]]\n[[Category:Technology in society]] \n[[Category:Politics and technology| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Politics}}\n\nThe combination of '''politics and technology''' covers concepts, mechanisms, personalities, efforts, and [[social movement]]s including but not necessarily limited to the [[Internet]] and other [[Information technology|information and communication technologies]] (ICTs).\n\nA growing body of scholarship has begun to explore how Internet technologies are influencing [[political communication]] and [[Participation (decision making)|participation]], especially in terms of what is known as the [[public sphere]].\n\nOne of the most influential and transformational information and communication technologies is the [[mobile phone]] or [[smartphone]], which can include: talk, text messaging, [[Internet]] and [[World Wide Web|Web]] access, [[electronic mail]], [[faxing]], pictures, video, and a wide variety of [[Mobile app|apps]]. Mobile devices are proving to increase political participation and are now even being portrayed as a voting gadget in even the [[least developed countries]]. Increased availability of this [[technology]] and subsequent access to the public sphere has enhanced the ability of individuals and groups to bring attention to and organize around specialized issues.<ref>Creeber, Glen. Digital Cultures: [understanding New Media]. Maidenhead: Open Univ., 2009. Print.</ref>\n\nMore recently, [[social media]] has emerged to become one of the main areas of influence for [[politics]], where millions of users are able to learn about politicians' policies and statements, interact with political leaders, organize, and voice their own opinions on political matters.<ref>{{cite book|title=Politics and the Twitter revolution : how tweets influence the relationship between political leaders and the public|last2=Bichard|first2=Shannon|date=2012|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=9780739165010|location=Lanham, MD|page=1|last1=Parmelee|first1=John}}</ref> For instance, the influence of mainstream rappers like Stormzy, Professor Green and Kano, on young voters through the use of social media. In the 2017 election the spike in youth turnout changed political analysis, with age replacing class for the first time as the best predictor of voting intention. In the 2019 election, of 18-25 year olds 56% voted Labour and 21% Conservative. Although this cannot ever be wholly contributed to the backing of Corbyn by young influencers, the effect cannot be underestimated. In a letter to the Guardian, put together by the Grime4Corbyn movement, many artists urge voters to back Labour to \u201cend austerity, rebuild our communities and take back the means to change our lives for the better\u201d. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/25/stormzy-backs-labour-in-election-with-call-to-end-austerity|title=Stormzy backs Labour in election with call to end austerity|last=Gayle|first=Damien|date=2019-11-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>Securing the backing of Stormzy, one of the UK\u2019s biggest recording artists, is a major coup for the Labour party and after lending his support in 2017, Stormzy was credited in part for the \u201cyouthquake\u201d that boosted Corbyn\u2019s party in that year\u2019s election. \n\nThere are also a wide variety of online tools that are meant to promote political participation and combat the spread of misinformation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paularmstrongtech/2018/03/01/how-technology-is-really-going-to-change-politics-in-the-next-20-years/|title=How Technology Is Really Going To Change Politics In The Next 20 Years|last=Armstrong|first=Paul|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> A [[comparison of civic technology platforms]] can be useful in differentiating the different services offered by each platform.\n\n== The digital public sphere ==\nThe idea of the [[public sphere]] has generally come to be understood as the open social spaces and [[public space]]s in which private citizens interact and share information and ideas relevant to the society. These can include, for example, town halls, public squares, markets, coffee shops, or what ancient Greeks called [[agora]]s. Many scholars have argued that these spaces are vitally important for creating and maintaining an active and informed public in a democratic society.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/freespaces00sara|title=Free spaces : the sources of democratic change in America|last=Evans|first=Sara M.|last2=Boyte|first2=Harry C.|date=1992|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0226222578|edition=2nd|location=Chicago|pages=|oclc=24669015}}</ref>\n\nIn [[J\u00fcrgen Habermas]]' book  ''[[The Structural Transformation of the Public Sphere|The Structural Transformation of the Public Sphere \u2013 An Inquiry into a Category of Bourgeois Society]]'', he defines the public sphere as \"a realm of social life in which public opinion can be formed.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The structural transformation of the public sphere : an inquiry into a category of bourgeois society|last=J\u00fcrgen|first=Habermas|publisher=|year=1962|isbn=978-0262081801|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=|oclc=18327374}}</ref> In principle, the public sphere should be open to all citizens, and free from influence from governments or private businesses. Habermas goes on to argue that:<blockquote href=\"Digital rights\">\"A portion of the public sphere is constituted in every conversation in which private persons come together to form a public. They are then acting neither as business or professional people conducting their private affairs, nor as legal consociates subject to the legal regulations of a state bureaucracy and obligated to obedience. Citizens act as a public when they deal with matters of general interest without being subject to coercion; thus with the guarantee that they may assemble and unite freely, and express and publicize their opinions freely.\"<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>[[Howard Rheingold]] argues that, \"There is an intimate connection between informal conversations, the kind that take place in communities... and the ability of large social groups to govern themselves without monarchs or dictators.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The virtual community : homesteading on the electronic frontier|last=Howard.|first=Rheingold|date=2000|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0262681216|edition= Rev. |location=Cambridge, Mass.|oclc=44162557}}</ref> Rheingold and others<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dahlgren|first=Peter|date=2006|title=The Internet, Public Spheres, and Political Communication: Dispersion and Deliberation|journal=Political Communication|volume=22|issue=2|pages=147\u2013162|doi=10.1080/10584600590933160}}</ref> have also gone on to argue that virtual spaces created through the [[Internet]] and related [[Information and communications technology|information and communications technologies]] have led to the emergence of a new type of digital public sphere. Some scholars have conceptualized this alternately as a virtual public sphere<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Papacharissi|first=Zizi|date=2002|title=The virtual sphere|journal=New Media & Society|language=en|volume=4|issue=1|pages=9\u201327|doi=10.1177/14614440222226244|issn=1461-4448}}</ref> or a networked public sphere,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shirky|first=Clay|date=2011|title=The Political Power of Social Media: Technology, the Public Sphere, and Political Change|jstor=25800379|journal=Foreign Affairs|volume=90|issue=1|pages=28\u201341}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Twitter and tear gas : the power and fragility of networked protest|last=Zeynep|first=Tufekci|publisher=|year=2017|isbn=9780300215120|location=New Haven|pages=|oclc=961312425}}</ref> while still others have similarly described what they call a networked society<ref>{{Cite book|title=Communication power|last=Castells|first=Manuel|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2013|isbn=9780191510434|edition= 2nd|location=Oxford|pages=|oclc=855022865}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Networks of outrage and hope: social movements in the Internet age|last=Castells|first=Manuel|publisher=Polity|year=2015|isbn=9780745662855|edition= 2nd|location=Cambridge|pages=|oclc=795757037}}</ref> or networked publics.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Networked Publics|last=Varnelis|first=Kazys|publisher=MIT Press|others=Annenberg Center for Communication (University of Southern California)|year=2008|isbn=9780262285483|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=|oclc=283798198}}</ref> Essentially, these new virtual spaces can be used in much the same way as traditional, offline spaces; that is, as a \"free space\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Democratic phoenix : reinventing political activism|last=Pippa|first=Norris|date=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0521811774|location=Cambridge, UK|pages=|oclc=48943689}}</ref> to discuss and debate ideas of public importance. Just as the public sphere is a combination of \"every conversation in which private persons come together to form a public\"<ref name=\":0\" /> the digital public sphere also comprises all forms of [[new media]], such as [[chat room]]s, website comment sections, and [[social media]], in which private citizens engage in discourse as a public. Virtual spaces may overlap or interact with offline spaces as well, forming what has been called \"hybrid networks\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lim|first=Merlyna|date=2015|title=A CyberUrban Space Odyssey: The Spatiality of Contemporary Social Movements|url=https://www.academia.edu/16240525|journal=New Geographies|language=en|volume=7|pages=117\u2013123|via=}}</ref>\n\nMany scholars argue that social media affords increasing opportunities for political discourse and mobilization within the digital public sphere.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Loader|first=Brian D.|last2=Mercea|first2=Dan|date=2011|title=Networking Democracy? Social media innovations and participatory politics|journal=Information, Communication & Society|volume=14|issue=6|pages=757\u2013769|doi=10.1080/1369118X.2011.592648|url=http://openaccess.city.ac.uk/5528/1/Networking%20Democracy%20iCS%20Intro%2014%206%20%28amended%29.pdf}}</ref> Research has shown that increased use of social media correlates with increases in certain types of political engagement and [[Participation (decision making)|participation]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boulianne|first=Shelly|year=2015|title=Social media use and participation: a meta-analysis of current research|journal=Information, Communication & Society|volume=18|issue=5|pages=524\u2013538|doi=10.1080/1369118X.2015.1008542}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kahne|first=Joseph|last2=Bowyer|first2=Benjamin|date=2018|title=The Political Significance of Social Media Activity and Social Networks|journal=Political Communication|volume=35|issue=3|pages=470\u2013493|doi=10.1080/10584609.2018.1426662}}</ref> The digital public sphere thus has the potential to enliven democratic culture<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/viralspiralhowco0000boll|title=Viral spiral : how the commoners built a digital republic of their own|last=David.|first=Bollier|date=2008|publisher=New Press|isbn=978-1595583963|location=New York|oclc=227016731}}</ref> and enhance the ability of citizens to challenge the political and economic power of governments and corporations<ref name=\":1\" /> such as through online [[protest]]s, [[activism]] campaigns, and [[social movement]]s.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Digitally enabled social change : activism in the Internet age|last=Earl|first=Jennifer|last2=Kimport|first2=Katrina|publisher=MIT Press|year=2011|isbn=9780262015103|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=|oclc=639573767}}</ref> Other scholars have also highlighted, alongside [[economic globalization]], the role of Internet technologies to reach across national borders to contribute to a growing transnational public sphere.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.press.umich.edu/11707|title=Globalizations and Social Movements|date=2000|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=9780472097210|editor-last=Guidry|editor-first=John|location=Ann Arbor, MI|language=en|doi=10.3998/mpub.11707|editor-last2=Kennedy|editor-first2=Michael|editor-last3=Zald|editor-first3=Mayer}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Transnational activism in Asia : problems of power and democracy|last=Piper|first=Nicola|last2=Uhlin|first2=Anders|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|isbn=978-0415315135|location=London|pages=|oclc=51817597}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms ==\n\n==== Social exclusion ====\nThe traditional, offline public sphere has been criticized for not being as inclusive in practice as it is in theory.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Habermas and the public sphere|last=|first=|publisher=MIT Press|year=1992|isbn=978-0262031837|editor-last=Calhoun|editor-first=Craig J.|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=|oclc=23650367}}</ref> For example, Feminist scholars like [[Nancy Fraser]] have argued that the public sphere has historically not been as open or accessible to [[Social exclusion|disadvantaged or marginalized groups]] in a society, such as women or people of color; therefore, such groups are forced to form their own separate public spheres, which she refers to as a ''counter-public'' or ''subaltern counter public'' (see {{slink|Public sphere#Counterpublics, feminist critiques and expansions}}).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fraser|first=Nancy|date=1990|title=Rethinking the Public Sphere: A Contribution to the Critique of Actually Existing Democracy|jstor=466240|journal=Social Text|issue=25/26|pages=56\u201380|doi=10.2307/466240}}</ref>\n\nSome scholars contend that online spaces are more open and thus may help to increase inclusive political participation from marginalized groups.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schlosberg|first=David|last2=Dryzek|first2=John S.|date=2002|title=Digital Democracy: Authentic or Virtual?|jstor=26162195|journal=Organization & Environment|volume=15|issue=3|pages=332\u2013335|doi=10.1177/1086026602153011}}</ref> In particular, [[Anonymity|anonymous]] online spaces should allow all individuals to speak with an equal voice to others.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Deseriis|first=M.|date=2013|title=Is Anonymous a New Form of Luddism?: A Comparative Analysis of Industrial Machine Breaking, Computer Hacking, and Related Rhetorical Strategies|journal=Radical History Review|language=en|volume=2013|issue=117|pages=33\u201348|doi=10.1215/01636545-2210437|issn=0163-6545}}</ref> However, other have pointed out that many contemporary online spaces are not anonymous, such as [[Facebook]]. Avatars and social media profiles often portray an individual's offline identity, which can lead to practices of online discrimination and exclusion which mirror offline inequalities.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Digitizing race : visual cultures of the Internet|last=Lisa|first=Nakamura|date=2008|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|isbn=9780816653775|location=Minneapolis|pages=|oclc=214085023}}</ref> Now, more and more historically disadvantaged or marginalized groups are also using Internet technology to carve out new online spaces for their own \"networked counterpublics\" such as through the use of [[hashtag]]s like #Ferguson and [[Black Lives Matter|#BlackLivesMatter]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jackson|first=Sarah J.|last2=Foucault Welles|first2=Brooke|date=2015|title=Hijacking #myNYPD: Social Media Dissent and Networked Counterpublics|journal=Journal of Communication|language=en|volume=65|issue=6|pages=932\u2013952|doi=10.1111/jcom.12185|issn=0021-9916}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jackson|first=Sarah J.|last2=Foucault Welles|first2=Brooke|date=2016|title=#Ferguson is everywhere: initiators in emerging counterpublic networks|journal=Information, Communication & Society|volume=19|issue=3|pages=397\u2013418|doi=10.1080/1369118X.2015.1106571}}</ref>\n\n==== The digital divide ====\nAnother factor which affects access to the digital public sphere is the [[digital divide]], which refers to how people from [[Least Developed Countries|less developed countries]] tend to have less access to [[Information and communications technology|information and communications technologies]] compared to those from more [[Developed country|developed countries]]. For example, the most developed regions of the world, such as North America and Western Europe, have the highest [[Global Internet usage|Internet penetration rates]] at over 80% each, while the least developed countries such as in Africa and South Asia have less than 30% each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/269329/penetration-rate-of-the-internet-by-region/|title=Global regional internet penetration rate 2017 {{!}} Statistic|website=Statista|language=en|access-date=2018-07-01}}</ref> On the other hand, the reduced cost and increasing availability of mobile devices such as [[smartphone]]s throughout less developed regions is helping to reduce this disparity at an exponential rate. In just two years, between 2013 and 2015, the number of Internet users in developing nations has risen by 9%, according to the [[Pew Research Center]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2016/02/22/smartphone-ownership-and-internet-usage-continues-to-climb-in-emerging-economies/|title=Smartphone Ownership and Internet Usage Continues to Climb in Emerging Economies|date=2016-02-22|work=Pew Research Center's Global Attitudes Project|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Other research has shown, though, that even within more developed countries like the United States, the digital divide continues to persist between upper and lower socioeconomic classes<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brookings.edu/research/broadband-adoption-rates-and-gaps-in-u-s-metropolitan-areas/|title=Broadband adoption rates and gaps in U.S. metropolitan areas|last=Tomer|first=Adie|date=2015|work=Brookings|access-date=2018-07-01|last2=Kane|first2=Joseph|language=en-US}}</ref> and between different education levels.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/03/05/some-americans-dont-use-the-internet-who-are-they/|title=11% of Americans don't use the internet. Who are they?|date=2018-03-05|work=Pew Research Center|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Furthermore, scholars like [[Mark Warschauer]] argue that it is not just access to technology that matters, but the knowledge of how to put that technology to use in meaningful ways.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Technology and social inclusion : rethinking the digital divide|last=Mark.|first=Warschauer|date=2003|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0262232241|location=Cambridge, Mass.|oclc=50028800|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/technologysocial0000wars}}</ref>\n\n==== Use of Bots and Sock Puppets ====\nInternet bots, also known as a web robot, robot or simply bot, is a software application that runs automated tasks (scripts) over the Internet.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guenon des Mesnards|first=Nicolas|title=Detecting Influence Campaigns in Social Networks Using the Ising Model|journal=|volume=|pages=|arxiv=1805.10244|year=2018|bibcode=2018arXiv180510244G}}</ref> Typically, bots perform tasks that are both simple and structurally repetitive, at a much higher rate than would be possible for a human alone. The largest use of bots is in web spidering, in which an automated script fetches, analyzes and files information from web servers at many times the speed of a human. More than half of all web traffic is made up of bots. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/terms/web_crawler.htm|title=Web crawler|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> This aids in the detection of bots as through qualitative coding, softwares can confirm the presence of bots. An example would be the Bot-a-meter developed by Indiana University, where they evaluate 7 different factors to determine whether or not an accounts is a bot. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://botometer.iuni.iu.edu/|title=Botometer by OSoMe|website=botometer.iuni.iu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref> \n\nA Sock Puppet is an online identity used for purposes of deception<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2127107-sock-puppet-accounts-unmasked-by-the-way-they-write-and-post/|website=www.newscientist.com|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>. The term originally referred to a false identity assumed by a member of an Internet community who is pretending to be another person. This includes other misleading uses of online identities, such as those created to praise, defend or support a person or organization, to manipulate public opinion, block evasion, ballot stuffing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/opinion/our_view/our-view-bots-and-sockpuppets-are-deepening-the-political-divide/article_31fbbd42-1745-11e8-baec-db909ca5572d.html|title=Our View: Bots and sockpuppets are deepening the political divide|website=PostBulletin.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>. There is significant evidence to indicate that the [[Internet Research Agency]], a group of professional Russian Trolls, created fake accounts on major networking sites, online newspapers, to promote specific Ukrainian, Middle Eastern, and American political issues, even advocating for Trump as early as December 2015. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/feb/23/troll-steven-poole-word-of-week|title=What's the difference between a troll and a sockpuppet?|last=Poole|first=Steven|date=2018-02-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Leapfrog Democracies ==\n[[File:Estonian municipal elections 2013.png|thumb|This is the divide of the different political parties in Estonia where in the 2013 elections, over 133,000 people (roughly 21.2% of participating voters) voted over the Internet. The 2013 elections  were also the first elections to allow vote verification with mobile devices. ]]\nLeapfrog democracies<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iftf.org/future-now/article-detail/leapfrog-democracies-personal-democracy-forum/|title=IFTF: Leapfrog Democracies @ Personal Democracy Forum|website=www.iftf.org|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> developed in the field of industrial organization and economic growth. It was a term first used at the Personal Democracy Forum in 2014. The basic concept of [[leapfrogging]] is that small and incremental innovations lead allow radical innovations with new firms or countries to \"leapfrog\" old and ancient ones, including with different governmental institutions and ideas. Countries that have huge developments that more typically advanced countries might only have much later. \n\n==== Tunisia ====\nAn example of this is the new [[Tunisia|Tunsia]] constitution. Learning from America and other countries, Tunisia developed a constitution that provides more rights that typical constitutions with issues concerning climate change, healthcare, women's rights, and workers' rights. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thinkprogress.org/4-ways-tunisia-is-now-more-progressive-than-the-united-states-9879ae93d105/|title=4 Ways Tunisia Is Now More Progressive Than The United States|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> They have provided rights that the United States' government does not cover for its citizens. Tunisia has set the stage for many other countries to follow in their footsteps including Egypt, Libya, Yemen, and Syria. Although these countries' attempts at democracies have not been nearly as successful as Tunisia's constitution. \n\n==== Estonia ====\nAnother example of a Leapfrog democracy is Estonia being one of the first countries to use online voting. Nearly 99% of their public services are available online, and a reported 44% of Estonia citizens use the online services. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://e-estonia.com/solutions/e-governance/i-voting/|title=i-Voting|website=e-Estonia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> [[Electronic voting in Estonia|Electronic Voting in Estonia]] has been occurring since 2005 and can cast votes through an app on their mobile device. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kalevleetaru/2017/06/07/how-estonias-e-voting-system-could-be-the-future/|title=How Estonia's E-Voting System Could Be The Future|last=Leetaru|first=Kalev|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> Through Estonia's national ID infrastructure, National ID cards have the ability to perform cryptographic functions to authenticate their access to different websites and make legally binding signatures on documents if needed. These cards work through the use of two different RSA key pairs. However, there are still some drawbacks of this voting process as there are inadequate procedural controls that change several times or are not followed, lax operational security, and insufficient transparency. These weaknesses can allow for client side attacks on the voting system.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Springall|first=Drew|date=|title=Security Analysis of the Estonian Internet Voting System|url=http://delivery.acm.org/10.1145/2670000/2660315/p703-springall.pdf?ip=52.119.73.232&id=2660315&acc=OA&key=4D4702B0C3E38B35%2E4D4702B0C3E38B35%2E4D4702B0C3E38B35%2E638B5282305ABE89&__acm__=1573545079_a022b85b1c91f97241681af5cb678b9b|journal=|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1145/2670000/2660315/p703-springall|doi-broken-date=2020-03-30|via=}}</ref>\n== Presence of online tools for political participation ==\n\nWith the increasing use of technology in the political sphere, many new platforms have emerged in an attempt to provide unbiased information to the general public in a manner that is easy access to all. The idea of spreading unbiased information has become a popular platform for many apps to get started on. Many of these apps hope to be able to spread this information so that voters may be more educated about the political sphere and make more of an informed decision when voting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paularmstrongtech/2018/03/01/how-technology-is-really-going-to-change-politics-in-the-next-20-years/|title=How Technology Is Really Going To Change Politics In The Next 20 Years|last=Armstrong|first=Paul|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> Some more examples include Liquid.us, Countable<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.countable.us/|title=Contact your Reps, Influence Congress, Vote on Bills|website=www.countable.us|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>, Capitol Bells<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.capitolbells.com/splash/|title=Capitol Bells|website=www.capitolbells.com|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>, Fiscalnote<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fiscalnote.com/|title=Homepage|website=FiscalNote|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>, and Councilmatic<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://councilmatic.org/|title=Councilmatic - Your local city council, demystified|last=Councilmatic|website=Councilmatic|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. Technology is progressing rapidly to making a significant impact on our future campaigns. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iop.harvard.edu/get-involved/study-groups/technology-innovation-and-politics-led-sonal-shah|title=Technology, Innovation and Politics led by Sonal Shah|website=The Institute of Politics at Harvard University|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> A [[comparison of civic technology platforms]] highlights the similarities and differences between different online tools used for political participation. \n\n==== PopVox ====\nAn example of this is PopVox, as they provide a holistic view of every bill and resolution that has passed or is currently in discussion with our government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popvox.com/|title=Your direct connection to lawmakers|website=www.popvox.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> Popvox also provides a platform for voters to share their opinions on different bills being discussed in Congress at the moment, and from the start of the app over 350,000 people have used the app from across the country to share their opinions on bills and become more informed. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/sarahmckinney/2014/02/01/the-future-of-political-engagement-is-here-and-its-called-popvox/|title=The Future Of Political Engagement Is Here (And It's Called POPVOX)|last=McKinney|first=Sarah|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n==== iSideWith ====\niSideWith is an application that seeks to provide voters with a more educated guess of who they would politically side with<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isidewith.com/|title=America's most popular voting guide for elections, political issues, candidates, and poll data|website=iSideWith|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. They have an in-depth survey on their website that asks about the users' political opinion on common issues discussed or debated within the government currently to give the voter a ranking of which politician best aligns with what stance they have on the current political sphere<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isidewith.com/political-quiz|title=2019 Political Quiz|website=iSideWith|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>. This gives voters more of an educated guess of who they should be casting their vote for. The more time the voters spend filling out the survey, the more accurate the results will align with their political stance. \n\n==== Change.org ====\n[[File:Change.org.jpg|thumb|The logo and slogan for change.org]]\nChange.org is a website that allows for people to take a stance on something they agree or disagree with and actually petition for others to rally behind their cause<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.activistfacts.com/organizations/530-change-dot-org/|title=Change.org {{!}} Funding sources, staff profiles, and political agenda {{!}} Activist FactsActivist Facts|website=Activist Facts|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>. People can search up petitions that have been started already concerning a cause that they may feel strongly about or they have the option of starting their own. The website displays past successful petitions that have made an impact and the petition does not necessarily have to be related to politics as well. There are many different surveys started by different people that could just be targeting different issues within their neighborhood but can range up to a social issue that they believe the whole world should be aware about. \n\n==== D21 ====\nD21 is a platform that allows people to participate in voting on issues through a form of \"modern democracy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.d21.me/|title=D21 {{!}} Participation and voting in municipalities, schools and companies.|website=en.d21.me|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> It is also known as the Jane\u010dek Method which allows people to cast both a negative and a positive vote<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cmu.edu/news/stories/archives/2016/march/better-way-for-voters.html|title=Alumnus Gives Voters A Better Way to Decide - News - Carnegie Mellon University|last=University|first=Carnegie Mellon|date=2016|website=www.cmu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. They wish to inform users more accurately about different issues happening within their community and provide them with a platform for them to be able to voice their opinions on. This is a platform that is used mainly in the Czech Republic to target corruption within the Czech government. Though it has not yet been used in any general elections, the Jane\u010dek Method has been used in several participatory budgeting programs around the world, including  New York City in the United States<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://civichall.org/civicist/new-york-city-tests-digital-ballot-in-participatory-budget-vote/|title=New York City Tests Digital Ballot in Participatory Budget Vote|website=Civic Hall|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. The Czech government introduced the game Prezident 21 which is an interactive website created to aid people in familiarizing themselves with the D21 system<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prezident21.cz/|title=Prezident 21|last=www.benes-michl.cz|first=Bene\u0161 & Michl|website=www.prezident21.cz|language=cs|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>.  \n\n==== Verified Voting ====\nVerified Voting is a website uses its online presence to discourage the movement of voting towards the more digital age. Specifically having a section about Internet Voting, they speak about the dangers and information leaks that come with using the internet or anything digital to cast votes, even with blockchain. Verified Voting defines internet voting to even include email or fax voting or any voting through an online portal. This is due to the fact that any form of electronic voting can cause the vote to be susceptible to a large number of security threats including cyber-attacks that can skew voting results and preferences<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.verifiedvoting.org/resources/internet-voting/|title=Internet Voting {{!}} Verified Voting|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>. According to NIST, it is difficult to make sure that votes are coming from verified and registered voters and it has not been changed in transit. This is difficult to verify over the internet and thus makes casting votes in person and through paper ballets more effective and safe, even with the flaws that it may have<ref>{{Cite document|last=Regenscheid|first=Andrew|last2=Hastings|first2=Nelson|title=A Threat Analysis on UOCAVA Voting Systems|year=2008|url=https://www.nist.gov/system/files/documents/itl/vote/uocava-threatanalysis-final.pdf|id=NISTIR 7551|pages=78|publisher=NIST|doi=10.6028/NIST.IR.7551}}</ref>.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[:Category:Regulation of technologies]]\n* [[Cultural lag]]\n* [[Digital rights]]\n* [[E-democracy]]\n* [[E-government]]\n* [[Electronic voting]]\n* [[Hashtag activism]]\n* [[Internet activism]]\n* [[Internet censorship]]\n* [[Media activism]]\n* [[Neo-Luddism]]\n* [[Netizen]]\n* [[Online deliberation]]\n* [[Public hypersphere]]\n* [[Technocracy]]\n* [[Technology policy]]\n* [[Comparison of civic technology platforms]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Politics by issue|Technology]]\n[[Category:Technology in society]] \n[[Category:Politics and technology| ]]\n", "name_user": "Hqb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEstonia:fix broken doi", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Politics_and_technology"}
{"title_page": "Fonix", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name = Fonix\n| logo = Clare Fonix Logo.png\n| company_type = Private\n| foundation = {{Start date|2006}}\n| location = [[London]], UK\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| founder = Will Neale, Rob Weisz\n| key_people = Rob Weisz<br />([[Chief executive officer|CEO]]), Marcus Kern<br />([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])\n| investors =\n| industry =\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| num_employees =\n| subsid = \n| url = {{URL|http://www.fonix.com/}}\n| programming_language = \n| ipv6 = \n| alexa = \n| website_type = \n| registration = \n| num_users = \n| language = \n| current_status = Active\n| screenshot = \n| caption =\n}}\n\n'''Fonix''' provides a [[mobile payment]]s and [[mobile messaging]] platform and is based in [[London]]. Its services are used by the media, entertainment, [[Telecommunication|telecoms]], enterprise and [[commerce]] sectors<ref name=Skeldon>{{cite web|last1=Skeldon|first1=Paul|title=Fonix and Impulsepay fly the flag for carrier billing in Tech Track 100|url=http://www.telemediaonline.co.uk/fonix-impulsepay-fly-flag-carrier-billing-real-world/|website=Telemedia Online|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> and Fonix has connections to all of the UK mobile networks. When consumers make payments, they are charged to their mobile phone bill. This service can be used for ticketing, content, cash deposits and donations.<ref name=Skeldon/>\n\nThe company was founded in 2006<ref>{{cite web|last1=n/a|title=Tech Track 100|url=http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/fonix-mobile/|website=Fast Track|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> and it has partnerships with [[Vodafone]] (of which it is a platinum partner),<ref>{{cite web|last1=n/a|title=Accredited Partners|url=https://b2benablers.vodafone.co.uk/partners/accredited-partners|website=Vodafone|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> [[EE Limited]], [[Telef\u00f3nica UK Limited]] and [[Hutchison 3G]]. Fonix's clients include [[tastecard]], [[Sport Relief]], [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]], [[Children in Need]], [[DMG Media]] and others.\n\nThe current [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] is Rob Weisz.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fonix: Tech Track 100|url=http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/fonix-mobile/|website=Fast Track|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== How it works ==\nFonix's service works by charging digital payments to the mobile phone bill, either via [[Mobile payment#Direct operator billing|Carrier Billing]] or [[Short Message Service|SMS]] Billing.<ref>{{cite web|last1=PYMNTS|title=Fonix To Handle BuyGameCredit Purchases On Xbox Live, PlayStation|url=http://www.pymnts.com/news/payment-methods/2016/fonix-buygamecredit-xbox-playstation-purchases/|website=PYMNTS|accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref> Fonix also offers [[messaging]] solutions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skeldon |first1=Paul |title=Mr |url=https://www.telemediaonline.co.uk/85969-2/ |accessdate=23 January 2019 |agency=World Telemedia |publisher=World Telemedia}}</ref> \n\n=== Carrier billing ===\n[[Application programming interface|APIs]] are used to charge users to their phone bills through desktop, mobile or [[Mobile app|app]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=n/a|title=Fonix: Tech Track 100|url=http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/fonix-mobile/|website=Fast Track|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nFonix's Carrier Billing services can be used for ticketing (e.g. parking tickets and cinema tickets), content (e.g. paying for film or magazines) and cash deposits.<ref name=Skeldon/>\n\n=== SMS billing ===\nFonix's API charges customers to their phone bills via SMS.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Alert Logic Product Marketing Team|title=Fonix Mobile - Mobile and billing system security in Amazon Web Services (aws)|url=https://www.alertlogic.com/blog/fonix-mobile-mobile-and-billing-system-security-in-amazon-web-services-(aws)/|website=Alert Logic|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref> This means that customers can purchase services or make charitable donations and are charged by sending the text message.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Skeldon|first1=Paul|title=BBC Children in Need breaks all time text to donate record with Fonix|url=http://www.telemediaonline.co.uk/bbc-children-in-need-breaks-all-time-text-to-donate-record-with-fonix/|website=Telemedia Online|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Skeldon|first1=Paul|title=Heart Radio embraces mobile listeners whose heart voice shortcodes - volume increase dramatically|url=http://www.telemediaonline.co.uk/heart-radio-embraces-mobile-listeners-whos-heart-voice-shortcodes-volume-increase-dramatically/|website=Telemedia Online|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe service is most commonly used for digital purchases, such as content, donations, voting, competitions and polls.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Liggero|first1=Rebecca|title=Rob Weisz on introducing mobile payments in the online gambling industry|url=http://calvinayre.com/2015/11/16/business/introducing-mobile-payments-for-online-gambling-bl-video/|website=Calvin Ayre|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Messaging ===\n\nFonix's messaging services have the capability to send and receive [[SMS]] online, via an [[API]] or via [[Short Message Peer-to-Peer|SMPP]]. [[Rich Communication Services|RCS]] messaging can be used to send richer message content.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Giles |first1=Hannah |title=Fonix joins Google\u2019s RCS Messaging Early Access Program |url=https://blog.fonix.com/fonix-joins-googles-rcs-messaging-early-access-program-ca9995851f45 |accessdate=23 January 2019 |publisher=Fonix Mobile}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nFonix was originally named '''Orca Digital'''<ref>[https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/orca-digital-uk#/entity Orca Digital]</ref> and was founded in 2006 in [[Chiswick]], [[London]]. Orca Digital focused upon [[mobile telephony]] and providing interactive services to the media and entertainment sectors.<ref>{{cite web|last1=n/a|title=Orca Digital launches VoiPay \u2013 a new premium web telephony platform|url=http://www.mynewsdesk.com/uk/pressreleases/orca-digital-launches-voipay-a-new-premium-web-telephony-platform-694693|website=My News Desk|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Orca Digital relaunched as Fonix Mobile under [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] Rob Weisz. At this point, the business became focused upon [[Mobile payment|mobile operator payments]] and mobile messaging services to a range of sectors including media, [[Charitable organization|charity]], [[Telecommunication|telecoms]], enterprise, gaming and entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|last1=n/a|title=Tech Track 100|url=http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/fonix-mobile/|website=Fast Track|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014, Fonix has secured contracts with [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=n/a|title=Channel 5 Select Fonix For Two Year Agreement For All Mobile Interactive Services|url=http://aimelink.org/channel-5-select-fonix-for-two-year-agreement-for-all-mobile-interactive-services/|website=aime|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref> [[Sport Relief]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=n/a|title=Sport Relief Legal|url=http://www.sportrelief.com/legal.|website=Sport Relief|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref> [[Children in Need]]<ref>{{cite web|title=ViewRanger keeps The One Show Rickshaw Challenge riders on track|url=http://www.cambridgenetwork.co.uk/news/viewranger-keeps-the-one-show-rickshaw-challenge-riders-on-t8203/|website=Cambridge Network|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref> and [[tastecard]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Awards Preview \u2013 Most Effective Mobile Payment Solution|url=http://mobilemarketingmagazine.com/awards-preview-most-effective-mobile-payment-solution-2016/|website=Mobile Marketing|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 and 2016, Fonix was listed in the [[Tech Track 100|Sunday Times Hiscox Tech Track]], ranking 34th and 28th respectively.<ref name=Skeldon/> In 2015 and 2016, Fonix ranked 50th and 37th in the [[Deloitte Fast 50]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Skeldon|first1=Paul|title=Fonix ranks 50th in the 2015 Deloitte Technology Fast 50 2015 after two years of trading|url=http://www.telemediaonline.co.uk/fonix-ranks-50th-in-the-2015-deloitte-technology-fast-50-2015-after-two-years-of-trading/|website=Telemedia Online|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fast 50 Winners 2016|url=http://www.fast50.co.uk/2016-winners/2016-winners.aspx|website=Deloitte|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref> In 2015 and 2016, Fonix ranked 363rd and 238th respectively in the  [[Deloitte Fast 500|Deloitte Technology Fast 500]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 Technology Fast 500TM Europe, Middle East & Africa (EMEA) Ranking|url=https://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/global/Documents/Technology-Media-Telecommunications/gx-deloitte-tmt-emea-fast500-2015-rankings.pdf|website=Deloitte|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fast 500 WInners|url=https://www2.deloitte.com/us/en/pages/technology-media-and-telecommunications/articles/fast500-winners.html|website=Deloitte|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref> In 2016 and 2017, Fonix won the [http://www.momas.co.uk/ Moma Award] for the Not for Profit/Charity Mobile Strategy/Campaign of the year. This was to recognise their use of [[Short Message Service|SMS]] for collecting [[Gift Aid|gift aid]] for the 2015 [[Children in Need]] Campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=Momas 2016|url=http://www.momas.co.uk/momas/momas-2016#22952|website=Momas|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.fonix.com/}}\n* [https://zensend.io/ Zensend home page]\n\n[[Category:Mobile payments]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the London Borough of Hounslow]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox dot-com company\n| na